    "48-year-old woman with photosensitive rash -Correctly identifies porphyria cutanea tarda (PCT) as the most likely diagnosis.",
    "-Recognizes the significance of family history, dark urine, and photosensitivity.",
    "-Considers other porphyrias (variegate porphyria).",
    "-Appropriately rules out liver transplantion and thalomide as standard therapies, understands the role of phlebotomy and hydroxychloroquine in PCT treatment.",
    "-Places excessive emphasis on normal ferritin levels, overlooking that phlebotomy can still induce remission even with normal iron stores."
